Introduction¶

For this project, the TMBD dataset will be investigated. TMBD is a very famous website for movie revues and information, containing a multitude of data centered around the movies, who directed them, who starred in them, their genres, an overview of the movie, how much were these movies liked, how much they made, and how much was spent on them.

There are many questions that could be asked in this data-set and here are some examples I thought about

  • Is budget related to revenue?
  • Does employing multiple directors improve the quality of the movie?
  • Which genres are more liked?
  • Does the popularity of the imply a higher revenue?


The goal is to find answers to as many of these questions as possible. While The direct questions will be limited, their scope will try to encompass as much of these questions as possible

Data Cleaning¶

The following list represents the steps I have taken in cleaning the data

  1. Removed some irrelavent or too incomplete features like
    • Homepage
    • Overview
    • Production Companies
    • Keywords
    • tagline
    • Cast
  2. removed duplicates
  3. seperate genres into different columns, renaming them with genres, put them in lower case and remove spaces to make them easier to follow
  4. Fill empty directors with NA
  5. Redefine Directors into Solos (S) and Cooperates (C)

Now all the features have the same number of features, except genres that would be kept as a reference

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Research Question 1: How different are cooperating directors compared to solo directors?¶

Directors usually work solo as shown in the above cells, they outnumber directors work together by almost 10111 movie of an 10865 movie data set
This trend is most likely based on the availability of directors to begin with, however does the hiring of multiple directors affect the quality of the movie at all?
Usually the quality in this case is measured by how popular or high earning they are

So in this section we will how the few movies that had multiple directors performed have improved or otherwise, looking at the popularity score, revenue and votes

There is also a small pattern study, as whether the runtime of a movie affects the quality, and how high of runtime either solo and non solo directors.

Research Question 2: Is genre related to popularity?¶

Multiple movies from different genres were made over the years, some were movies had several genres built into them, but which genres were conistently the more successful over the years? Also does popularity improve the revenue or not?

The below charts are mostly incomprehensible since most genres overlap, we would need other charts¶

It is meant to show how much the movie changed popularity and revenue have change over the years, however all genres overlap and there are many movies, we could seperate them and analyse them individually. This may not be helpful either, we could try to remove all the lesser movies that earned too little to be considered influential, as many genres have their share of botched movies.

Popularity under 1 will be removed thereafter

The following cells seperate all the genres into different part of the dictionary so they could be processed separetly

In [92]:
revenues_values = []
genres_labels= []
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])
ax.axis('equal')
for genre in genresDictionary:
    mean_rev = genresDictionary[genre].revenue.mean()
    if mean_rev==0 or math.isnan(mean_rev):
        continue
    
    genres_labels.append(genre[:genre.find("genre")-1])
    revenues_values.append(mean_rev)
    
revenues_values, genres_labels = (list(t) for t in zip(*sorted(zip( revenues_values,genres_labels))))
explode = np.full(shape=len(revenues_values),fill_value=0.05)    
ax.pie(revenues_values, labels = genres_labels, autopct='%.1f%%', explode = explode)

ax.set_title('Pie chart')
plt.title("Best genres by average revenue")
plt.show()

This pie chart here shows a decorrelation between it and the previous pie chart, while science fiction is the most popular, it is not by default the most earning.

Horror movies as well generally earn more than TV movies, which could be simply explained that again, no one watches a TV movie in theatre, because they are on TV.

Most genres are generally out of place an unalligned when comparing their revenue to popularity, generally showing that movies may not earn more, but they can be appreciated for what they are later on.

Conclusions¶

For question one, I am able to conclude that solo directors are usually more successful that cooporating directors, the biggest limitation was the imbalance in data as I could not make a clear case since most movie are directed by solos, which doesn't allow for a complete and definite picture. This however also implies that directors prefer to work solo as it is more practical to have one creative mind than many opossing ones.

Furthermore as shown by the scatter plots, the solos tend to have more, they have more freedom in the runtime, they are more popular, and they get more votes. A person may love Spielberg and go to watch one of his movies specifically, but it is rare that two visionaries work together in a movie, therefore cooporating directors are usually the not so well known directors who don't always make mind blowing movies, and at worst they are forced by the producing companies to work together, with limitations to runtime. This I assume is the reason why solos earn more (the turnover is very high), more popular (directed by amazing directors) and therefore by correlation get more positive reviews in form of high votes.

For question two, The biggest problem I faced was managing the genres, I had to resort to the simplest way I know, dictionaries, to keep track of all movies that fall into each genre, and there was still the big issue that most movies have overlapping genres, like action/adventure/thriller. Which might be the reason why some of these genres are over-represented. If this limitation is to be ignored however and any genre is considered as a group, the research become a bit more torrelable. If we define popularity as loyalty, then definitely genres are related to popularity, as it shown by documentaries and westerns, which have the highest votes despite being the lowest on every other possible scale and that very little of them were made with popularity above 1. Otherwise, by looking at popularity score and revenue, the most earning genres (sci-fi, adventure, action, thriller) are also some of the most popular, these movies capture the popular immagination and encourages people to watch them for the sense of adventure and discovery. This is unlike drama, comedies and romance, which are mostly predictable and boring.

Whatever is the case, the most consistently disliked and underperforming genres would be horror and TV-movies. Despite the earlier being produced very frequently.
